title: Emergency Management Directors
descr: Plan and direct disaster response or crisis management activities, provide disaster preparedness training, and prepare emergency plans and procedures for natural (e.g., hurricanes, floods, earthquakes), wartime, or technological (e.g., nuclear power plant emergencies or hazardous materials spills) disasters or hostage situations.
alt_titles: Emergency Services Director, Emergency Response Specialist, Emergency Response Coordinator, Civil Defense Director, Emergency Preparedness Coordinator, Disaster Response Director, Emergency Planning and Response Manager, Emergency Planner, Emergency Management System Director (EMS Director), Emergency Management Coordinator, Response Coordinator, Civil Preparedness Officer, Relocation Director, Public Safety Director, Program Management Specialist, Fire Management Specialist, Emergency Services Program Coordinator
experience: A considerable amount of work-related skill, knowledge, or experience is needed for these occupations. For example, an accountant must complete four years of college and work for several years in accounting to be considered qualified.
education: Most of these occupations require a four-year bachelor's degree, but some do not.
job_training: Employees in these occupations usually need several years of work-related experience, on-the-job training, and/or vocational training.
example: Many of these occupations involve coordinating, supervising, managing, or training others. Examples include real estate brokers, sales managers, database administrators, graphic designers, conservation scientists, art directors, and cost estimators.
svp_desc: Individuals workers typically need anywhere from between 2 and 4 years- up to 10 years- to learn the techniques, acquire the information, and develop the facility needed for average performance in specific situations.
